; SPDX-License-Identifier: PMPL-1.0-or-later
; INTENT.contractile — Purpose and scope for tma-mark2
; Helps LLM/SLM agents understand what this repo IS and IS NOT.
;
; Part of the contractile family: MUST, TRUST, DUST, INTENT, ADJUST

; ── Definitions ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
;
; INTENT (noun)
;   The purpose contractile. Defines what this repository IS, what it is
;   NOT (anti-purpose), and which architectural decisions are load-bearing.
;   Without INTENT, LLMs drift into scope creep, reverse key decisions,
;   or add features that belong in a different repo.
;
; Scope:
;   INTENT governs the conceptual boundaries of the project — its reason
;   for existing, its domain, and its relationship to the ecosystem.
;   It does NOT specify implementation details (that's MUST and code).
;
; Relationship to other contractiles:
;   - MUST: INTENT explains WHY certain MUSTs exist. If you don't
;     understand a MUST, read INTENT first.
;   - TRUST: The "ask-before-touching" section in INTENT maps directly
;     to TRUST.trust-deny for the most sensitive areas.
;   - ADJUST: INTENT's anti-purpose should include "this software is
;     NOT only for users with perfect vision/hearing/mobility."
;   - DUST: When INTENT changes (repo pivots), related DUST entries
;     should be created for the abandoned direction.
;
; ── End Definitions ──────────────────────────────────────────────

(intent-contractile
  (version "1.0.0")
  (repo "tma-mark2")

  ; === Purpose (what this repo IS) ===
  (purpose
    "tma-mark2 is an offline-first desktop marking tool for Open University
     tutors. It replaces the legacy Java eTMA application with an Elixir/Phoenix
     LiveView implementation. It parses .fhi student submissions, provides a
     real-time marking interface, and exports graded .docx feedback files. The
     application runs entirely on the tutor's local machine with no cloud
     dependency, using CubDB for embedded storage and Burrito for cross-platform
     single-binary distribution."
  )

  ; === Anti-Purpose (what this repo is NOT — prevents scope creep) ===
  (anti-purpose
    "This is NOT a learning management system (LMS) — it only handles the
     marking step of the assignment lifecycle. It is NOT a cloud application —
     student data must never leave the tutor's machine. It is NOT a general
     document editor — it processes .fhi and .docx only. It is NOT a student-
     facing tool — only tutors use it. It is NOT only for users with perfect
     vision — the LiveView UI must be accessible (see ADJUST.contractile)."
  )

  ; === Key Architectural Decisions That Must Not Be Reversed ===
  (architectural-invariants
    ("Elixir/OTP for fault tolerance — supervision trees ensure crash recovery")
    ("CubDB for storage — embedded, crash-proof, no external database server")
    ("Phoenix LiveView for UI — server-rendered, real-time, no SPA framework")
    ("Rust NIFs for crypto — Argon2id via Rustler, not pure Elixir")
    ("Burrito for distribution — single binary for all 6 target platforms")
    ("Offline-first — no feature may require network connectivity")
    ("Bebop for sync protocol — binary serialization, not JSON/protobuf")
  )

  ; === Sensitive Areas (if in doubt, ask) ===
  (ask-before-touching
    "native/tma_crypto/ — Rust NIFs, security-critical, changes affect BEAM stability"
    "lib/etma_handler/fhi.ex — FHI parser, proprietary format, needs domain knowledge"
    "lib/etma_handler/crypto.ex — security module, Argon2id config"
    "mix.exs releases config — Burrito targets, affects all platform builds"
    "config/runtime.exs — production configuration, affects deployed instances"
    ".machine_readable/ — checkpoint files, format is specified"
    "bebop/schemas/ — binary protocol definitions, affects sync compatibility"
  )

  ; === Ecosystem Position ===
  (ecosystem
    (belongs-to "standalone")
    (depends-on ("phoenix" "cubdb" "rustler" "burrito" "cachex" "sweet_xml"))
    (depended-on-by ("ou-tutors"))
  )
)
